3.  As the municipal engineer, he or she will 

(i)  carry out topographical and geotechnical surveys; 
(ii)  conduct municipal infrastructure material investigations and tests; 
(iii)  review detailed designs to ensure that subproject design is based on the analysis 
of  alternatives  and  least-cost  solutions,  and  takes  into  account  disaster 
prevention measures proposed by the World Bank and other donors; 
(iv)  draw up detailed cost estimates and appropriate contract packaging; 
(v)  evaluate tenders; 
(vi)  supervise construction and oversee quality control; 
(vii)  administer  contracts,  monitor  physical  and  financial  progress,  and  process 
contract variations and other contractor’s claims; 
(viii)  coordinate  with  MEES  on  conducting  initial  environmental  examinations  for 
concerned subprojects to ensure that appropriate mitigation measures would be 
undertaken during project implementation; and 
(ix)  prepare quarterly progress and project completion reports in his or her respective 
field. 

2.  Road and Bridge Engineer (30 person-months) 

4.  A road and bridge engineer will be required for the service of 30 person-months to assist 
the PIU in the Ministry of Transport and Communications (MOTC) in implementing the road and 
bridge components of the Project. Specifically, the road and bridge engineer will report to the 
project manager in MOTC and will 

(i)  carry out topographical and geotechnical surveys; 
(ii)  conduct road and bridge material investigations and tests; 
(iii)  review detailed designs to ensure that subproject design is based on the analysis 
of  alternatives  and  least-cost  solutions,  and  takes  into  account  disaster 
prevention measures proposed by the World Bank and other donors; 
